frameDefinitions: Two (or more) people (the Parties, also encodable as Party_1 and Party_2) come to an agreement committing them to carrying out an Obligation.
This frame characterizes the likelihood that a Hypothetical_event will happen as a position on a scale of impossible to inevitable.

An Entity that has characteristics which change over time is at a point or in a phase of its development in which, compared to other actual or expected stages of development, it possesses extremely high or low powers or intensity.
A Speaker declares that they will no longer be involved with the Content.
A Cognizer faces a choice on some Issue.
The Outcome of a contest is described in terms of the Margin between what would be required for victory and the actual Outcome.
frameExamples: No arms <t>compromise</t> between the two parties is expected before the end of 2012.
The Tang Dynasty was the <t>high point</t> of the Silk Road's importance.
That will only be possible if and when the IRA <t>renounces</t> armed struggle.
Dave Hayes <t>wavered</t> about moving to California because so many of his friends are in Baltimore.
The Basque nationalists won a <t>narrow</t> victory in the regional elections on Sunday.
listRoleDefinitions: The individual or individuals that form the more prominent (i.e., agentive) party to the compromise, as compared with <fen>Party_2</fen>. That is, <fen>Party_1</fen> is generally encoded as the External Argument of verbs, and peripheral FEs that do not make reference to the event itself generally make reference to <fen>Party_1</fen>. Thus <fen>Manner</fen> is construed to be that of <fen>Party_1</fen>, not necessarily that of <fen>Party_2</fen> or the group of <fen>Parties</fen> as a whole.
The semantically (and grammatically) less prominent participant (or group of participants) in the compromise. It is generally encoded within a prepositional phrase (e.g. headed by <m>with</m>).
An expression of the commitment made by the <fen>Parties</fen> .
<fen>Topic</fen> is a description of the domain covered by the compromise.
The group of individuals portrayed as equally involved in reaching a compromise.
This role identifies the <fen>Place</fen> where the compromise occurs.
This role identifies the <fen>Place</fen> where the compromise occurs.
A numerical representation of the probability that a Hypothetical_event will occur.
A metaphorical representation of the position on the scale of likelihood that the Hypothetical_event will occur.
The event that is expected to happen with a certain likelihood.
An concrete or abstract entity that possesses characteristics that change over time.

A point or phase in time when, viewed across the actual or expected development, the <fen>Entity</fen>'s powers have reached an extreme high or low point. The point or phase is often identified metonymically by reference to a product created by the <fen>Entity</fen> or an event involving the <fen>Entity</fen>.
The <fen>Speaker</fen> is the person who communicates their cessation of association with the <fen>Content</fen>.
The idea that the <fen>Speaker</fen> no longer associates with, whether it be an activity, a propostion, or a group.
<fen>Medium</fen> is the physical entity or channel used by the <fen>Speaker</fen> to transmit the statement of renunciation.
The time when the statement is made.
The role specifies the place where the statement takes place.
The <fen>Cognizer</fen> is the person who repeatedly changes their mind about which of the <fen>Options</fen> to choose.
The <fen>Options</fen> are the alternative courses of action or the alternative physical or concrete entities that the <fen>Cognizer</fen> can choose from.
The <fen>Issue</fen> is a question about a course of action or a choice between items.

When there is an explicitly separate construal of the <fen>Options</fen>, <fen>Option_1</fen> is the first-mentioned alternative, typically in the form of a from-PP. When it is clear that  the <fen>Cognizer</fen> actually acted on their choice, <fen>Option_1</fen> is the alternative they embraced first before pursuing <fen>Option_2</fen>.

When there is an explicitly separate construal of the <fen>Options</fen>, <fen>Option_2</fen> is the second-mentioned alternative, typically in the form of a to-PP. When it is clear that  the <fen>Cognizer</fen> actually acted on their choice, <fen>Option_2</fen> is the alternative they embraced after abandoning <fen>Option_1</fen>.
This role denotes the <fen>Time</fen> interval during which the <fen>Cognizer</fen> keeps changing their mind about which of the <fen>Options</fen> to select.
This role identifies the <fen>Place</fen> where the <fen>Cognizer</fen> keeps changing their mind between the <fen>Options</fen> that present themselves.
The <fen>Outcome</fen> of a contest whose <fen>Margin</fen> is under consideration.
The difference between the minimum required for victory and the actual <fen>Outcome</fen>.
A modifier expressing  the deviation of the <fen>Value</fen> from what is expected given the <fen>Outcome</fen> and the <fen>Value</fen> indicated by the target.
The generally implicit <fen>Value</fen> of the <fen>Margin</fen>.
